The 155th [[The Boat Race|Boat Race]] took place on 29 March 2009.  Oxford's crew was the heaviest in the event's history and which featured five Olympic rowers, including silver medallist [[Colin Smith (rower)|Colin Smith]] and bronze medallist [[George Bridgewater]].  Cambridge took an early lead, only to be caught and overtaken by Oxford who won the race by three-and-a-half lengths.

In the reserve race, Cambridge's Goldie defeated Oxford's Isis, while Oxford won the [[Henley Boat Races#Women's Boat Race|Women's Boat Race]].

==Background==
[[The Boat Race]] is an annual competition between the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of Cambridge]].  First held in 1829, the competition is a {{convert|4.2|mi|km}} race along [[The Championship Course]] on the [[River Thames]] in southwest London.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/uk/london/10719622/University-Boat-Race-2014-spectators-guide.html | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate = 6 June 2014 | date = 25 March 2014 |title = University Boat Race 2014: spectators' guide | first = Oliver |last =Smith}}</ref>  The rivalry is a major point of honour between the two universities and followed throughout the United Kingdom and worldwide.<ref name=CBC>{{cite news|title=Former Winnipegger in winning Oxford-Cambridge Boat Race crew|date=6 April 2014|publisher=[[CBC News]] |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/former-winnipegger-in-winning-oxford-cambridge-boat-race-crew-1.2600176|accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref>  Oxford went into the race as reigning champions, having won the [[The Boat Race 2008|2008 race]] by six lengths,<ref name=results>{{Cite web | url = http://theboatrace.org/men/results| publisher = The Boat Race Company | title = Boat Race <U+2013> Results| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref> while Cambridge led overall with 79 victories to Oxford's 74 (excluding the "dead heat" of 1877).<ref>{{Cite web | url= http://theboatrace.org/men/classic-moments-the-1877-dead-heat | publisher = The Boat Race Company | title = Classic moments <U+2013> the 1877 dead heat | accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref>  The race was sponsored by [[Xchanging]] for the fifth consecutive year.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-12888300 | publisher = BBC News| title = Boat Race sponsor Xchanging to end contract | date = 29 March 2011 | accessdate = 5 June 2014}}</ref>

==Crews==
[[File:Start - 2009 Boat Race - Oxford.jpg|thumb|Oxford crew at the start]]
[[File:Cambridge VIII at Stakeboat - 2009 Boat Race.jpg|thumb|Cambridge crew at the start (cox Dowbiggin has her hand raised to indicate she and her crew are not ready to start)]]
The Oxford crew (sometimes referred to as the "Dark Blues")<ref name=blues>{{Cite web | url = http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2003/apr/06/theobserver | work = The Observer | title = Dark Blues aim to punch above their weight | date = 6 April 2003 | accessdate = 8 April 2014 }}</ref> weighed an average of {{convert|8|lb|kg}} per rower more than the Cambridge crew (sometimes referred to as the "Light Blues"),<ref name=blues/> making them the heaviest in Boat Race history.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/7952429.stm | title = Oxford weigh in as heaviest ever | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 19 March 2009 | accessdate = 6 June 2014 }}</ref>  Oxford fielded five rowers who had featured at the [[Rowing at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Summer Olympics]]: [[Colin Smith (rower)|Colin Smith]] won silver for Great Britain,<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/rowing/6255972/Great-Britains-Olympic-silver-medallist-Colin-Smith-quits-rowing-despite-London-2012.html | title = Great Britain's Olympic silver medallist Colin Smith quits rowing, despite London 2012 | first = Rachel | last = Quarrell | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate = 14 June 2014 | date = 2 October 2009}}</ref> while [[Ante Ku<U+0161>urin]] rowed for Croatia,<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/CRO/summer/2008/ROW/ | title = Croatia Rowing at the 2008 Beijing Summer Games | publisher = Sports Reference | accessdate = 14 June 2014}}</ref> New Zealander [[George Bridgewater]] won a bronze in the coxless pair,<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/rowing/5050599/George-Bridgewater-confident-that-Oxford-are-hitting-top-form.html | title = George Bridgewater confident that Oxford are hitting top form | accessdate = 14 June 2014 | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | date = 25 March 2009 | first = Rachel | last = Quarrell}}</ref> [[Sjoerd Hamburger]] rowed for The Netherlands,<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/summer08/fanguide/athlete?id=18990| publisher = ESPN | title = Sjoerd Hamburger| accessdate = 14 June 2014}}</ref> and Tom Solesbury for Great Britain.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.independent.co.uk/student/postgraduate/mbas-guide/is-there-a-link-between-management-and-rowing-1665880.html | work = [[The Independent]] | title = Is there a link between management and rowing? | first = Peter | last = Brown | accessdate = 14 June 2014 | date = 9 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=heavy>{{Cite web |url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/rowing/5018166/Oxford-University-crew-weigh-in-as-the-heaviest-ever-ahead-of-the-Boat-Race.html | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | title = Oxford University crew weigh-in as the heaviest ever ahead of the Boat Race | first = Rachel| last = Quarrell | date=19 March 2009 | accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref>  Cambridge's crew contained five returning [[Blue (university sport)|Blues]] to Oxford's three.<ref name=heavy/>

The crews for the race were as follows:

