==Race==
Cambridge won the toss and elected to start from the Surrey station.<ref name=oubc>{{Cite web | url = http://www.ox.ac.uk/media/news_stories/2009/090330.html | title = Boat Race triumph for Oxford again | publisher = [[University of Oxford]] | accessdate = 6 June 2014 | date = 30 March 2009 }}</ref>  Cambridge's cox Dowbiggin raised her hand to indicate that she was not ready to start just as Umpire [[Boris Rankov]] started the race.<ref name=tel763>{{Cite web | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/rowing/5071763/Oxford-defeat-Cambridge-in-155th-Boat-Race.html | title = Oxford defeat Cambridge in 155th Boat Race | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate = 6 June 2014 | date = 29 March 2009| first = Rachel | last = Quennell }}</ref>  This allowed Oxford the initiative and they took an early lead.  Cambridge slowly edged their way back into contention, and held a half-a-length lead at the two-mile mark.<ref name=oubc/>  At [[St Paul's School, London|St Paul's School]], Cambridge were two-thirds of a length ahead before a series of oar clashes and umpire warnings forced the boats apart.  A larger clash, between Cambridge's Monaghan and Oxford's Smith,<ref name=tel763/> took place by [[Chiswick Eyot]] before Oxford made the better recovery and quickly pushed out to secure a clear-water lead.<ref name=tel763/>  Cambridge failed to threaten, and Oxford won by three-and-a-half lengths.<ref name=tri/>

In the reserve race, Isis defeated Goldie by four lengths, completing the race in a time of 17 minutes 24 seconds, for their second consecutive win.<ref name=results/> Oxford won the Women's Boat Race by one-and-a-quarter lengths, hosted at Henley on 22 March 2014.<ref name=oubc/><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://theboatrace.org/women/results| publisher = The Boat Race Company | title = Women's Boat Race <U+2013> Results| accessdate = 14 June 2014}}</ref>

==Reaction==
Oxford's boat club president Colin Smith said "it's a great, great feeling".<ref name=tri>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/rowing/7968614.stm | title = Oxford triumph in 155th Boat Race | date = 29 March 2009| accessdate = 20 April 2014| publisher = BBC Sport}}</ref>  He continued: "The difference between the two crews today was our power, aggression and stickability".<ref name=oubc/> Cambridge's Australian international Cubasch said "it's really devastating.  Sometimes you'd be happy with a silver but here it's dead last."<ref name=tel763/>  His coach, Chris Nilsson, admitted "at the end of the day, the stronger crew with the more power came through".<ref name=tri/>  Oxford coach Sean Bowden said "We just said 'get to halfway, and head for home<U+2019>, and they did a really good job".<ref name=tel763/>

